@flexiarg relationship-coherence/body-attunement
@title Meet the Body Where It Hurts
@sigils [🩸/身]
@keywords body, pain, endometriosis, cycle, attunement, non-fixing, tenderness, chronic
@audience correspondents holding a chronic-pain reality
@references [relationship-coherence/capacity-honoring relationship-coherence/rupture-repair]
@references-extra ["Instance of origin: 2026-06-04 — Julia, 'you may genuinely be more attuned to my body than I am... the moon has begun to pull on my womb.' Recurs as plainly-named flares met with non-fixing tenderness: 2026-06-06 'An endometriosis flare-up has made for a slightly complicated/painful morning'; 2026-05-11 'the monthly female horrors'; hot-water-bottle offers rather than solutions."]
@tone practical
@style pattern

! conclusion: When the body flares — endometriosis, the cycle, exhaustion — name it plainly and meet it with attuned, non-fixing tenderness (a hot water bottle, company, rest), not problem-solving.

  + context: Julia lives with chronic, cyclical pain; the correspondence names it directly rather than euphemising, and Joe responds with attunement (sometimes even anticipating a flare) and small comforts rather than fixes.

  + IF:
    the body is in pain or depleted in a bodily way, and the reflex is either to hide it or to try to solve it.

  + HOWEVER:
    non-fixing is not passivity (ignoring the pain fails too), and attunement must not tip into presuming to know the other's body better than they do — it is offered, not asserted.

  + THEN:
    name the flare plainly; respond with presence and small embodied comforts (hot water bottle, a quiet day, company); accept that the body sets the pace (see relationship-coherence/capacity-honoring).

  + BECAUSE:
    chronic pain met plainly and tenderly, without the pressure to be fixed, is far more bearable; attunement to the body is a deep register of being known.

  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: bodily pain is named without shame and met with comfort, not solutions. Failing when: it is euphemised/hidden, or 'help' becomes unwanted fixing. (Note: in this corpus the pattern is asymmetric — mostly Julia's body — which is itself worth seeing.)
